bourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (Down): habitational and ethnic name from Middle English <i>Scot</i> ‘man from Scotland’. There is no evidence that the surname denoted either of the earlier senses of <i>Scot</i> as ‘(Gaelic-speaking) Irishman’ or ‘man from Alba’, the Gaelic-speaking region of Scotland north of the river Forth. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English and Scottish: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Scot</i> (Old English <i>Scott</i>, possibly also Old Norse <i>Skotr</i>), only certainly attested in northern England.","English: variant of   Scutt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Scutt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Pierre.","Americanized form of Dutch   Schutte   ‘archer’.","English: nickname for a short person, from Middle English <i>scut(e)</i> ‘short’, or else for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>scut</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William John Scott was born in 1355, in Ashford, Kent, England, his father, Michael Scott, was 20 and his mother, Emma de Brabourne, was 25. He married Matilda de Cumbe in 1370. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1413, in Brabourne, Kent, England, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1355–1413":"1355–1413","1345–1447":"1345–1447","1345–1395":"1345–1395","1370–1447":"1370–1447","1335–1361":"1335–1361","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1447":"1447","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Ashford, Kent, England":"Ashford, Kent, England","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1355–1413":"1355–1413","1345–1447":"1345–1447","1345–1395":"1345–1395","1370–1447":"1370–1447","1335–1361":"1335–1361","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1447":"1447","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Ashford, Kent, England":"Ashford, Kent, England","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"fr":{"1355–1413":"1355–1413","1345–1447":"1345–1447","1345–1395":"1345–1395","1370–1447":"1370–1447","1335–1361":"1335–1361","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1447":"1447",